# ========================================
# ENVIRONMENT VARIABLES EXAMPLE
# ========================================
#
# Purpose: Template for environment variables
#
# IMPORTANT INSTRUCTIONS:
# 1. Copy this file and rename it to .env.local
# 2. Replace the example values with your actual values
# 3. NEVER commit .env.local to git (it contains secrets)
# 4. The .gitignore file should include .env.local
#
# What are environment variables?
# - Configuration values that can change between environments
# - Different values for development, testing, production
# - Keeps sensitive data (tokens, passwords) out of code
# - Can be changed without modifying code
#
# How to use:
# 1. Create .env.local file in project root
# 2. Add variables below with your values
# 3. Restart development server (Vite reads env files on startup)
# 4. Access in code: import.meta.env.VITE_API_URL
#
# ========================================

# ----------------------------------------
# API CONFIGURATION
# ----------------------------------------
#
# Purpose: Configure the Strapi backend URL
#
# What is this?
# - The base URL of your Strapi backend
# - All API requests will be sent to this URL
#
# Why configurable?
# - Development: http://localhost:1337
# - Production: https://your-strapi-domain.com
# - Different team members might use different ports
#
# Note: Must start with VITE_ to be accessible in frontend code
#
VITE_API_URL=http://localhost:1337


# ----------------------------------------
# DEVELOPMENT ONLY - AUTO-LOGIN (OPTIONAL)
# ----------------------------------------
#
# WARNING: Only for development! NEVER use in production!
#
# Purpose: Automatically log in during development
# Saves time by not requiring manual login after each page refresh
#
# How to use:
# 1. Log in to your Strapi backend manually
# 2. Get your JWT token (from browser DevTools > Application > Local Storage)
# 3. Paste the token here
# 4. Restart dev server
# 5. You'll be automatically logged in
#
# How to get JWT token:
# Method 1: From browser (easiest)
# - Log in to the app normally
# - Open DevTools (F12)
# - Go to Application tab > Local Storage
# - Find 'accessToken' and copy its value
#
# Method 2: From Postman (or similar)
# - Make POST request to http://localhost:1337/api/auth/local
# - Body: { "identifier": "your-email", "password": "your-password" }
# - Copy the 'jwt' value from response
#
# SECURITY WARNING:
# - This is a development convenience feature
# - NEVER commit your actual token to git
# - NEVER use this in production
# - Token gives full access to your account
#
# Uncomment and add your token if you want auto-login:
# VITE_DEV_JWT=your_jwt_token_here

# Optional: Also auto-set user data (must be valid JSON, no line breaks)
# VITE_DEV_USER_JSON={"id":1,"username":"yourname","email":"your@email.com"}


# ----------------------------------------
# OTHER CONFIGURATION (OPTIONAL)
# ----------------------------------------
#
# You can add more environment variables as needed
# Examples:
#
# VITE_APP_NAME=Strapi Posts App
# VITE_APP_VERSION=1.0.0
# VITE_ENABLE_ANALYTICS=false
# VITE_MAX_UPLOAD_SIZE=5242880


# ========================================
# NOTES FOR TRAINEES
# ========================================
#
# Why environment variables?
# ✅ Security: Keep secrets out of code
# ✅ Flexibility: Different values per environment
# ✅ Convenience: Change config without code changes
# ✅ Best Practice: Industry standard approach
#
# Naming Convention:
# - Must start with VITE_ for frontend access
# - Use UPPER_SNAKE_CASE
# - Be descriptive (VITE_API_URL not VITE_URL)
#
# Common Mistakes:
# ❌ Forgetting to restart dev server after changes
# ❌ Committing .env.local file to git
# ❌ Not using VITE_ prefix (variable won't be accessible)
# ❌ Using quotes around values (not needed)
#
# Git and Environment Files:
# - .env.example: Committed to git (safe, has no secrets)
# - .env.local: NOT committed (contains actual values/secrets)
# - .env: NOT committed (alternative to .env.local)
# - .gitignore: Should include .env.local and .env
#
# Accessing in Code:
# const apiUrl = import.meta.env.VITE_API_URL;
# const isDev = import.meta.env.DEV;  // boolean, true in development
# const isProd = import.meta.env.PROD;  // boolean, true in production
#
# ========================================
